Exposure A discrete piece of a claim that involves a single type of loss (for example, vehicle damage or bodily injury) to a specific claimant. Contains data to describe the exposure and to track the current status of the exposure. Many exposure fields are specific to certain types of exposures and will be left blank on other types.

    • assign

      public boolean assign(Group group, User user)
      Directly assigns the entity to the specified group and user by setting the assignedGroup and assignedUser fields.
    • If user or group is null returns false and nothing is done.
    • If user is the Autopilot, the Feature is enabled, and the entity is automatable, it proceeds with the assignment as usual.
    • If user is the Autopilot but the Feature is disabled or the entity not automatable it will make no changes and return false.
      • Specified by:
      assign in interface Assignable
      Specified by:
      assign in interface CCAssignable
      Parameters:
      group - The group to which the entity should be assigned
      user - The user to which the entity should be assigned
      Returns:
      true if the assignment is successful

    • assign

      public void assign(Key groupID, Key userID) throws com.guidewire.pl.system.exception.NoAssignmentFoundException, com.guidewire.pl.system.exception.IllegalAssignmentException
      Deprecated.
      Use autoAssign(Group, User) instead. Note that that method returns a boolean instead of throwing exceptions

      Invokes the Assignment Engine to assign the item to the specified group and user.

    • If userID is null, the item will be assigned using the group's assignment rules.
    • If userID is the Autopilot but the entity is not automatable, or the Feature is disabled, it will proceed as if userID were null.
    • If userID is not the Autopilot, assignment will be made directly to the group and user.
    • If userID is the Autopilot, the Feature is enabled, and the entity is automatable, assignment will be made directly to the group and user.

      • If the engine cannot assign the item to the requested group/user, it will throw an exception indicating the reason.

      If a user is specified, caller is responsible for ensuring that the user is a member of group.

      Note that since this method invokes the Assignment Engine, it may not be called from within an Assignment rule.
      Specified by:
      assign in interface Assignable
      Specified by:
      assign in interface CCAssignable
      Parameters:
      groupID - The group to which the item should be assigned - must be specified. If not known, use autoAssign(item) instead.
      userID - The user to which the item should be assigned; if null an appropriate user will be selected by group assignment rules.
      Throws:
      com.guidewire.pl.system.exception.IllegalAssignmentException - if the user does not have permission
      com.guidewire.pl.system.exception.NoAssignmentFoundException - if assignment could not be made

    • assignByUserAttributes

      public boolean assignByUserAttributes(AttributeBasedAssignmentCriteria attributeBasedAssignmentCriteria, boolean includeSubGroups, Group group)
      Assigns an assignable item to a user who satisfies the constraints defined in the attributeBasedAssignmentCriteria parameter. This is done by:

      1) Find the set of users who are members of the supplied group, and optionally its subgroups, and who satisfy the supplied attribute-based search criteria. (If the group parameter is null, then no group restriction applies) 2) Select from the resulting set of users via the round-robin rotation mechanism. A separate round-robin state will be maintained for each unique assignment criteria entity and group.

      Specified by:
      assignByUserAttributes in interface Assignable
      Specified by:
      assignByUserAttributes in interface CCAssignable
      Parameters:
      attributeBasedAssignmentCriteria - the criteria to be satisfied by the selected user
      includeSubGroups - if true, searches all the users in any subgroups of the group parameter as well as those in that group. If false, only searches users in the group
      group - the group.
      Returns:
      true if the assignment is successful, false otherwise

    • assignGroupByGroupType

      public boolean assignGroupByGroupType(GroupType requiredGroupType)
      Deprecated.
      This method of assignment is deemed useless, because it always returns the first group found with the required type. Use assignGroupByRoundRobin() instead, so that the assignment will be rotated among the matching groups.
      Uses the group type group selector to choose the next subgroup under the "current" group (retrieved from the current state of the Assignment Engine) to receive the assignable. If there is no current group, the root group from the Assignment Engine is used.

      This method will search breadth-first through the group tree, starting with the current group, and will return the first group found with the approriate type.

      If invoked from outside an Assignment Rule, will take no action and return false.

    • assignGroupByLocation

      public boolean assignGroupByLocation(GroupType groupType, Address address, boolean directChildrenOnly, Group parentGroup)
      Assigns this entity to a group based on region assignments. This is done in the following manner:

      1) Based on the Region configuration, get the smallest zone containing the supplied address (in the US, this would typically be the zip code) 2) Search for the groups within the parameter group whose region assignment configuration includes that zip code. 3) If no group is found, repeat steps 1 and 2 with the next largest zone (in the US, county) 4) If no group is found, repeat steps 1 and 2 with the next largest zone (in the US, state) 5) If more than one group is found, then round-robin among the resulting groups based on the zone which was used to find the match.

      For example if we find no groups that match by zip but a few that match by county then assignment will round robin through the ones that match by county and will ignore any others that match by state. Matching is case-insensitive.

      Search is restricted to the sub-groups of the specified group and optionally all of its children. If there is no specified group, then the root group is used. Note that starting from the root group is potentially costly in performance time. If invoked from outside an Assignment Rule, this method will take no action and return false.

      Specified by:
      assignGroupByLocation in interface Assignable
      Specified by:
      assignGroupByLocation in interface CCAssignable
      Parameters:
      groupType - Only groups whose GroupType property matches this value will be considered
      address - An address to use for location-based assignment
      directChildrenOnly - if this parameter is false the selector will round-robin not only through the parameter group but also through all its subgroups.
      parentGroup - The group whose subgroups will be considered for assignment
      Returns:
      true if the assignment is successful, false otherwise

    • assignGroupByRoundRobin

      public boolean assignGroupByRoundRobin(GroupType groupType, boolean includeSubGroups, Group parentGroup)
      Uses the round robin algorithm to choose the next group to receive the assignable.

      The round-robin algorithm is basically a simple "eenie-meenie-miney-moe" rotation. No current assignment load is taken into account, but each Group's load factor is used to determine relative assignment frequency; essentially, a group with a lower load factor than the others' is periodically skipped.

      The round-robin rotation for each group type (and boolean value) is independent of the others, so only identical calls will impact the user who is "next" in the rotation.

      If no group is specified, the root group will be used instead. Note that starting from the root group is potentially costly in performance time.

      When group type is specified, the load factor is NOT used.

      Specified by:
      assignGroupByRoundRobin in interface Assignable
      Specified by:
      assignGroupByRoundRobin in interface CCAssignable
      Parameters:
      groupType - Only groups whose GroupType property matches this value will be considered
      includeSubGroups - if this parameter is true the selector will round-robin not only through the parameter group's immediate children but also through all its subgroups.
      parentGroup - The group whose subgroups will be considered for assignment
      Returns:
      true if the assignment is successful, false otherwise

    • assignUserByLocationUsingProximitySearch

      public boolean assignUserByLocationUsingProximitySearch(Address address, boolean includeSubGroups, Group group)
      Assigns this entity to the user with the closest address to the specified address, measured by a great-circle distance along the surface of the earth. This includes the following steps:

      1) Geocode the supplied address which will serve as the center of the search. (If necessary, location may already be geocoded) 2) For each user in the specified group, compute the distance from their location (using their Contact entity's primary address) to the supplied location. 2a) If the includeSubGroups parameter is true, repeat this process with all of the descendant groups of the specified group 3) Return the user who is closest to the specified location

      If the geocoding attempt fails for the supplied location, an error will be logged and false returned

      Search begins with the users of the parameter group; it is an error if there is no group.

      Specified by:

    • assignUserByProximityWithSearchCriteria

      public boolean assignUserByProximityWithSearchCriteria(UserSearchCriteria usc, int cap, boolean includeSubGroups, Group group)
      Assigns this entity to a user based on a User Search by Proximity. This includes the following steps:

      1) Geocode the location which will serve as the center of the search, accessed through usc.getContact().getAddress(). (If necessary; the location may already be geocoded) 2) Finds a list of users who satisfy the user search criteria, which may include proximity restrictions. The specified cap is used to limit the number of users in this list; in the case of proximity restrictions, the users farthest from the search center are trimmed. 3) Use the round-robin algorithm to pick one of the users. This means that repeated, identical calls to this method will rotate through the resulting set of users to find the user to return.

      Note that the round-robin rotation is based on the exact UserSearchCriteria used. One implication of this is that the location used should be as general as possible (such as just a city, state or zip, rather than a specific street address) to get the benefit of the round-robin processing and reduce the load on the system.

      To always assign to the closest user, set the cap to 1.

      Note: while this can be used to do assignment without the proximity search parameters set (thus allowing a general "assignUserBySearchCriteria" capability), this is not recommended or the intent of this method. It is computationally expensive compared to other methods of non-proximity-based assignment and should be used with care.

      The user search criteria should be set up via gw.api.geocode.GeocodeScriptHelper.setupUserProximitySearch() in order to ensure that the proximity search criteria are set up properly.

      The group parameter may be null. If it is not null, it will be used as part of the search

      Specified by:
      assignUserByProximityWithSearchCriteria in interface CCAssignable
      Parameters:
      usc - a valid User Search Criteria, may not be null
      cap - If greater than zero, the maximum number of users to include for round robin from the search results. If -1, all users from the search results will be included in the round robin.
      includeSubGroups - if the sub group should be used for search
      group - The group from where the search should be conducted
      Returns:
      true if the assignment is successful, false otherwise

    • getCurrentAssignment

      public CCAssignable getCurrentAssignment()
      Deprecated.
      Depends on the Assignment Engine state; The idea of "secondary" assignment causes performance impact without adding any benefit. If used anywhere, remove “.CurrentAssignment” from the Gosu expression.
      This method exists to support the notion of "secondary" assignment in the Assignment Rules. "Secondary" assignments generally represented by UserRoleAssignment entities, are assignments of "roles" to users, separated from the single "primary" owner of the entity.

      It is generally desirable for Assignment rule writers to be able to re-use a single set of, say, Claim Assignment rules for both primary and secondary assignments. This method allows rules to be written in the form of Claim.CurrentAssignment.assignXXX() rather than Claim.assignXXX(). If the primary assignment is being performed, then getCurrentAssignment() will return the entity itself (in this case, the Claim). If a secondary assignment is being performed, then getCurrentAssignment() will return the UserRoleAssignment which is current being operated upon.

      Obviously, if an entity does not support secondary assignment (i.e. does not implement the UserRoleOwner interface), then rules do not need to use this method. Secondary assignments done outside of the Assignment Rules can simplay call the assignXXX methods directly on the UserRoleAssignment entity themselves, and therefore also do not require this method.

      Since this method is dependent on the Assignment Engine state, calling it outside of the Assignment Rules is illegal.

      Specified by:
      getCurrentAssignment in interface Assignable
      Specified by:
      getCurrentAssignment in interface CCAssignable
      Returns:
      the CCAssignable entity being operated on by the Assignment Engine. May be either the current entity or a UserRoleAssignment entity relating to the current entity.

    • getInitialReserve

      public Reserve getInitialReserve(TransactionSet transactionSet, CostType costType, CostCategory costCategory)
      Returns the initial reserve transaction of this exposure. The initial reserve is the saved reserve with a status of TransactionStatus.TC_SUBMITTING or TransactionStatus.TC_SUBMITTED that has the earliest update time. Excludes the transactions in the given TransactionSet if it is not null.

      Note this method only returns one reserve, though many reserve transactions may have been initially created at the same time and meet the given filter requirements. Also, this method has nothing to do with Claim Health Metrics that use a concept of initial reserves.

      This method used to return the Amount of the initial Reserve; add ".Amount" to the end to get the old return value (this is null safe in Gosu). It would also return BigDecimal.ZERO if the Amount was null, so you'll have to add a check for that null case, too. For example: 

         var amount = exposure.getInitialReserve(...).Amount
   amount = (amount == null ? BigDecimal.ZERO : amount)
      Parameters:
      transactionSet - reserves included in this TransactionSet is excluded from the determination of the initial reserve
      costType - only reserves that have this CostType are considered - if null, then all reserves are considered, regardless of CostType.
      costCategory - only reserves that have this CostCategory are considered - if null, then all reserves are considered, regardless of CostCategory.
      Returns:
      initial reserve of this exposure, or null if no match

    • getPaymentsIterator

      public Iterator<Payment> getPaymentsIterator(boolean newAndModifiedOnly)

      Constructs an Iterator to provide access to the Payment objects for this exposure. You can choose to get either all the payments or only the new and modified payments. If you choose to get all the Payment objects, then Payment objects in the current transaction are not be returned by the Iterator. This method is a much more efficient alternative to calling getTransactions() and iterating through all the transactions to find just the desired Payment objects.

      Note: When newAndModifiedOnly is false, the beans returned by this iterator are not guaranteed to be in the same bundle as this Exposure, and their bundle may not be editable. To edit the beans, you should add them to an editable bundle first.

      Parameters:
      newAndModifiedOnly - if true then only new and modified Payment objects for this exposure are returned. This includes payments for which only the line items were modified. Otherwise, if false then all Payment objects for the exposure are returned, including new and modified Payment objects, but excluding deleted Payment objects.
      Returns:
      an Iterator that returns Payment objects.

    • getPossibleCoverageSubtypes

      public CoverageSubtype[] getPossibleCoverageSubtypes(CoverageType coverageType)

      Returns an array containing the possible coverage subtypes for this exposure if the coverage type is set to the given value. Takes into account the exposure's type and excludes any coverage subtypes not available for this exposure's type. The coverage type is exposed as a parameter (rather than just being the current PrimaryCoverage value).

      You can use this method to ask "if the coverage type of this exposure was X, what subtypes are possible?". This may be useful in the UI for constructing reflection value ranges. For example, if the user selects a particular coverage type you can set the choice of coverage subtypes appropriately via reflection.

      Parameters:
      coverageType - the proposed coverage type. To use the current coverage type just use the result of getPrimaryCoverage().
      Returns:
      the array of possible coverage subtypes, or an empty array if there are none or if the coverageType parameter is null. Never returns null.

    • getPublicID

      public String getPublicID()
      The external ID for this entity.

      PublicID values are automatically created during the commit, if not previously set. The format is random, meeting security requirements based on current industry standards. For example:

      • pc:SYinDB2XTOgNZFs1NpxU8
      • pc:Sf8QS4N5RBS-h8_pj-Oy_
      • pc:SBwBzylneecSNr6_Ub4IO
      Your configuration code must not assume any particular format for PublicID values, in either the prefix or body portion of the string, or even assume the existence of a prefix. Do not make any assumptions at all about the content of a PublicID value, including expectations that values are sequential, numeric, or prefixed.

      You can subclass and override AbstractBundleTransactionCallback.afterSetIds(gw.pl.persistence.core.Bundle) if you need to see the value in the same commit. 

      
  var note = new Note(bundle)
  bundle.addBundleTransactionCallback(new AbstractBundleTransactionCallback() {
     override function afterSetIds(b : Bundle) {
       log.info("Created Note " + note.PublicID)
     }
  })
      Specified by:
      getPublicID in interface Editable
      Specified by:
      getPublicID in interface KeyableBean
      Specified by:
      getPublicID in interface Retireable
      Specified by:
      getPublicID in interface Versionable
      Returns:
      the external id.

    • pushAssignmentPopup

      public void pushAssignmentPopup(List<CCAssignableMethods> assignables)
      Called when assigning one or more manually assigned assignables - that is, assignables that are in the manual/pending assignment state, referenced by assignment review activities. This method brings up the assignment popup, to finalize the assignment of the assignables. The list of argument assignables is guaranteed to be non empty and only contains assignables of the same type as this object. The first entry in the assignables list will be this assignable.

      So, for example, this method might be called on a claim to bring up the assignment popup to assign the claim plus, maybe, other claims as well.

      This method should only be called from a PCF page (or in a method called from a PCF page)

      assignables - the items to be assigned. Guaranteed to be non empty, will contain this assignable plus, maybe, other assignables of the same type.

    • saveAndSetup

      public void saveAndSetup(Assignee assignee)

      Does all preprocessing work required to save an exposure, and then saves it. saveAndSetup performs the following steps:

      1. Sets the Exposure's claim order.
      2. Runs the "Pre-assign" ruleset on the exposure.
      3. Runs the segmentation engine on the exposure.
      4. Runs the strategy engine on the exposure.
      5. Runs the assignment engine on the exposure.
      6. Runs the workplan engine on the exposure.
      7. Runs the "Post-assign" ruleset on the exposure.
      8. Sets the exposure's status to "open".
      9. Create initial reserves.
      10. Commits the exposures's bundle (which will contain the exposure, activities, and other objects creating during the call).
      Parameters:
      assignee - the target assignee to which the exposure should be assigned

    • segment

      public void segment()
      Apply segmentation to this exposure. (This does both segmentation and strategy.) If all exposures on the claim are being segmented, consider using Claim.segmentAllExposures() for performance and caching.

    • setAvailableReserves

      public Reserve setAvailableReserves(CostType costType, CostCategory costCategory, BigDecimal newReserveAmount, User submittingUser) throws com.guidewire.cc.system.exception.ClosedClaimException, com.guidewire.cc.system.exception.ClosedExposureException, com.guidewire.pl.system.exception.InsufficientAuthorityException
      Sets the available reserves for this exposure to the given amount by creating a reserve that increases or decreases the currently available reserves. This method creates a new ReserveSet and Reserve transaction with the amount necessary to get the AvailableReserves for the matching ReserveLine to equal the newReserveAmount. This transaction amount might be positive if an increase is needed or negative if a decrease is needed. The ReserveSet is not run through pre-setup rules and is immediately submitted for approval. Unlike setting reserves in the UI, this method ignores any Reserve transactions on the same ReserveLine with a status of Pending Approval (since the AvailableReserves calculation does not include PendingApproval reserves). If the current AvailableReserves amount is already equal to newReserveAmount, then this method does not create a new Reserve nor ReserveSet, and returns null.
      Parameters:
      costType - The cost type for the reserve. This value cannot be null.
      costCategory - The cost category for the reserve. This value cannot be null.
      newReserveAmount - The amount the available reserves should be. The amount must be zero or greater, not negative.
      submittingUser - User submitting this reserve.
      Returns:
      the new reserve (Note: the amount of the returned reserve should not be changed) The method will return null if new reserve is not created.

    • touch

      public void touch()
      Set's the version of the bean to the next value (i.e. the bean version original value+1) Multiple calls to this method on the same bean will result in the same value being used for the version (i.e. it is idempotent). Calling this method will force the bean to be written to the database and participate fully in the commit cycle e.g. pre-update rules will be run, etc.

    • validate

      public ValidationResult validate(boolean validateClaim)
      Executes new exposure validation rules on the exposure, and returns a validation object containing any errors (if validation was successful, an empty validation object is returned). Note that this method has the side-effect of setting the validation level, and hence requires that the current user have Claim EDIT permissions, or will throw an exception.
      Parameters:
      validateClaim - Whether or not the exposure's claim should be validated as well. If true then the claim is validated before the exposure is validated.
      Returns:
      a ValidationResult containing 0 or more errors found.
